g.text: Temperature inside ℃, Temperature outside ℃ by Date time
In a beehive, temperature regulation is crucial for the
colony’s survival, especially in winter. Bees do not heat the
entire hive but focus on maintaining warmth within their
cluster, where temperatures can reach around 35°C at the
center. As heat rises, the area immediately above the
cluster remains warmer than other parts of the hive,
making overhead insulation beneficial for reducing heat
loss. Contrary to common belief, leaving a super of honey
on the hive does not burden the bees with extra heating;
instead, it acts as an insulator and stabilizes internal
temperatures. Additionally, the honey near the cluster
remains warm enough for consumption, ensuring the bees
have accessible food throughout colder months.
